ury paper age’s baseless fabric set the stage for contemporary digital media’s weightless production. Engagingly written and abundantly illustrated, Media Critique in the Age of Gillray highlights the fact that graphic culture has been overlooked as an important sphere for the production of critical and self-reflective discourses around media transformations and the visual turn in British culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEnglish wit and humor, PictorialzEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aPrintsxSocial aspectszEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aPrints, EnglishzEnglandy18th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Books & Reading.2bisacsh  aHenry Fuseli.  aJames Gillray.  aJohn Thomas Smith.  aWilliam Blake.  aballad sellers.  aculture.  adark media.  adefaced pictures.  aeighteenth-century London.  agraphic satire.  amass media.  apaper.  aphantasmagoria.  aprint culture.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076715540uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148752775440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487527754423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487527754/original  a978-3-11-076715-5  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK